snippet.textDisplay:
I’ll say it, this movie did 3 things wrong:

1) The fact that the murder was the obvious suspect. “Was it the nerdy cop who was interested in the author? Maybe it’s half of the family who wanted her to have “a gift.”” All Red herrings that shouldn’t have been Red herrings.

2) Politics was shown well (The young lib and cons kids were great), but added nothing! I don’t recall them talking about Asylum, so she may still be deported...

3) The ending Coffee Shot ruined the character. She was built up as the moral one, but also content with the whole family being screwed over? The movie showcased the them as being selfish at different points (some worse than others), but WHEN did the “knives come out?”
Their father killed himself... then they were told he was murdered... and then an assistant inherited the home they all grew up in (and $$$). WHO WOULDNT FLIP S@&T!?!

In conclusion: The illegal immigrant took money that would have gone to Americans (Lol, but really, she’s a horrible character)

snippet.textDisplay:
I actually did not like this movie. Everybody did the most convoluted, ridiculous things. It's all style and no substance. Don't even get me started on foolproof, conscience-related vomit as a plot device, but there were even worse things about it.

All Marta had to say was, "You know, he was talking about how much he loved morphine, and then I left my bag behind. I don't know what happened after I left". Problem FUCKING SOLVED. Nobody needs to lie, slit their own throat, hide toxicology reports or climb in phony windows. And even if he still slit his own throat in a misguided attempt to save her, you're telling me it would be unusual for somebody to zonk themselves out before doing something that painful?

And what kind of investigator notices a blood spot on somebody's shoe and doesn't send it away for immediate testing? Letting a person of interest tag along and have access to all the evidence in the vague hope that they'll incriminate themselves? And then not even watching them closely?
snippet.textOriginal:
I actually did not like this movie.  Everybody did the most convoluted, ridiculous things.  It's all style and no substance.  Don't even get me started on foolproof, conscience-related vomit as a plot device, but there were even worse things about it.

All Marta had to say was, "You know, he was talking about how much he loved morphine, and then I left my bag behind.  I don't know what happened after I left".  Problem FUCKING SOLVED.  Nobody needs to lie, slit their own throat, hide toxicology reports or climb in phony windows.  And even if he still slit his own throat in a misguided attempt to save her, you're telling me it would be unusual for somebody to zonk themselves out before doing something that painful?

And what kind of investigator notices a blood spot on somebody's shoe and doesn't send it away for immediate testing?  Letting a person of interest tag along and have access to all the evidence in the vague hope that they'll incriminate themselves?  And then not even watching them closely?
